      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"trickle-down\" idea assumes businesses can easily absorb higher labor costs without raising prices, but in rural areas with thin margins, that simply doesn't happen. If you raise wages, you either lose customers to cheaper competitors or are forced to cut back on hiring and benefits, which ultimately hurts the very workers you're trying to help. While higher wages do provide immediate relief to employees, the long-term economic benefit to the local community is often lost when businesses struggle to survive or reduce their overall spending.",
